arch:property.oc:show_val: L18 is ashy fill below the hard packed clayey fill in L17 under the mudbrick wall in L7. The locus continues north of where the wall once was. We changed the southern two meters of the trench to L18 because there was an ash layer split into two loci, L15 north of the wall and L13 south of the wall. Because they were identical I decided to connect them once the wall was excavated.
loose ashy fill with very fine particles and harder mudbrick debris mixed

this is a fine ash mixed with harder mudbrick debris areas, at the west half of the locus we came upon a reed impression, L19, similar to those found in trench A8, we took samples of the fill picked off above the reed impression and closed the locus.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
